                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 163.&#8212;<name
                                                type="person" key="697">Private O. J.
                                                Richardson</name>, <name type="organization"
                                                key="228">Co. C, 108th N. Y.</name>, was admitted
                                                <date type="admit" when="1863-11-23">Nov. 23,
                                                1863</date>, in a comatose condition; pulse 120,
                                        just perceptible; tongue dry and fissured; breast and
                                        abdomen covered with sudamina and feet and legs cold.
                                        Stimulants were freely given and warmth applied to the feet.  He died on <date type="death" when="1863-11-27">the 27th</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination <date type="autopsy" when="1863-11-28">thirteen hours after death</date>: Much emaciation;
                                        feet becoming gangrenous. Lungs, heart and spleen normal;
                                        Peyer's glands enlarged and ulcerated; solitary glands of
                                        large intestine enlarged and ulcerated; mesenteric glands
                                                enlarged.&#8212;<hi rend="italic"><name
                                                  type="person" key="210">Act. Ass't Surg. W. H.
                                                  Letterman</name>, <name type="hospital" key="162">Douglas Hospital</name>, Washington, D. C.</hi></p>                        
